<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level READ ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_[scope]_case_agent` CONDITIONAL read access to
    `x_[scope]_case_task` records inside the scoped application `x_[scope]`.
    The condition restricts read to task records whose PARENT CASE is
    "Assigned only" to the calling user (i.e., parentCase.assigned_agent ==
    current user OR parentCase.assigned_group contains current user, per AAP
    Section 0.5.6 "Assigned only" definition). This is the READ counterpart
    to the sibling WRITE ACL at
    ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_write_agent_assigned.xml; the advanced ACL
    script body is byte-identical between the two records by design, since
    the same predicate gates both read and write access on case_task rows.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_agent row, mirrored at the
        case_task table level per AAP Section 0.5.1 row
        "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/x_[scope]_case_task_*.xml"
        ("Mirror ACL pattern at task level; case_agent can write only tasks
        where parent case is 'Assigned only'"):
            | Role                  | Create | Read              | Write             | Delete |
            | x_[scope]_case_agent  |  Yes   | Yes Assigned only | Yes Assigned only |  No    |
        This file authors the single "Read = Assigned only" cell for the
        case_task table. The "Yes" Create cell is authored by
        ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_create_agent.xml; the "Yes Assigned
        only" Write cell by
        ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_write_agent_assigned.xml; the "No"
        Delete cell is enforced by the deliberate ABSENCE of any
        x_[scope]_case_task_delete_agent.xml file (ServiceNow record-level
        ACLs are deny-by-default: a role with no granting ACL for an
        operation cannot perform that operation).
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - "Assigned only" definition:
            "Assigned only = cases where assigned_agent = current user OR
             assigned_group contains current user."
        Because case_task rows do NOT carry their own assigned_group /
        assigned_agent fields (per AAP Section 0.5.7 the case_task schema is
        case, subject, type, status, assigned_to, due_date), the predicate
        is evaluated against the PARENT CASE referenced by current.case.
        The script below dereferences current.case via getRefRecord() and
        applies the same two-clause predicate (parentCase.assigned_agent ==
        currentUserId, OR parentCase.assigned_group membership) used by the
        case-level ACLs. This ensures the operational invariant: an agent
        can read a task if and only if they can read the task's parent
        case.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
            "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write;
             case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has
             full access."
        The middle clause ("case_agent cannot access unassigned cases") is
        the central correctness criterion of THIS file: this ACL must DENY
        read on a case_task row whose parent case has the agent neither as
        assigned_agent nor as a member of the assigned_group. In ServiceNow,
        denying read also causes the record to be excluded from list views,
        related lists, report results, and dashboard widget rows for the
        unauthorized agent - so a robust read-ACL is the linchpin of the
        entire least-privilege design at the task level. The validation is
        exercised by the round-trip-verify procedure
        (../scripts/round_trip_verify.md) in which a demo case_agent
        attempts to read seeded demo tasks whose parent case is NOT
        assigned to them - the platform must filter those rows out of every
        surface (case-form Related List, task list, "My overdue tasks"
        report on the Agent Workspace dashboard, etc.).
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig
        map." This ACL is the table-level READ binding for the mid-tier
        scoped role on the task domain.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): "The 'Assigned only' condition for case_agent is
        encoded in the ACL condition script as a query: assigned_agent =
        current.sys_id OR assigned_group IN current.user_group_membership.
        No global ACLs are touched." For case_task the same query shape is
        applied but on the parent case row reached via current.case.
      - Section 0.5.5 (State-Machine Transition Map): the Resolved
        transition is gated by the rule "All linked x_[scope]_case_task
        records have status = Closed". For an agent to drive a case to
        Resolved, they must first SEE all linked tasks on the case form's
        Related List - which requires READ access to those tasks. Without
        this ACL, agents could not even view their own tasks on cases
        assigned to them, breaking the entire Resolved transition path
        and the operational task-closure UX.
      - Section 0.4.4 (User Interface Design - Internal user UI): "Related
        Lists on the case form for both case_task (parent = current case)
        and case_party (parent = current case)." Without this READ ACL,
        the case_task Related List on the case form would render empty
        for case_agent users, even on cases assigned to them - because
        related-list rendering executes a query against case_task that the
        platform filters through THIS ACL on a per-row basis.

    Why this is the READ counterpart to the WRITE ACL:
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6 the case_agent role is granted both Read and
      Write under the same "Assigned only" condition. It would be both
      operationally inconsistent and a usability anti-pattern to allow an
      agent to write a task they cannot read, or read a task they cannot
      otherwise interact with. The two ACLs differ only in:
        - <operation>      "read" (this file)                  vs "write"
        - <sys_id>         MD5("x_[scope]_case_task.read...")  vs MD5("x_[scope]_case_task.write...")
        - <sys_update_name> *_read_agent_assigned              vs *_write_agent_assigned
        - <description>    references "read" semantics         vs "write/update" semantics
      The CDATA script body is byte-identical between the two records by
      design; both encode the same predicate per AAP Section 0.5.6.

    Why current.case.getRefRecord() (NOT direct field access on `current`):
      This is a TABLE-LEVEL ACL on x_[scope]_case_task, so at evaluation
      time the platform binds `current` to the CASE_TASK row being read
      - NOT to the parent case. Direct access of current.assigned_agent
      / current.assigned_group would fail because those columns do not
      exist on x_[scope]_case_task per the AAP Section 0.5.7 task schema
      (the task has only case, subject, type, status, assigned_to,
      due_date). To reach the parent case's assignment fields, the script
      must dereference current.case (a Reference field on case_task whose
      target is x_[scope]_case per AAP Section 0.5.7) by calling
      .getRefRecord() - the GlideElementReference-supplied accessor that
      returns a fully-populated GlideRecord of the referenced row. This
      is in contrast to the parallel x_[scope]_case_read_agent_assigned
      ACL where `current` IS the case row and direct field access works.

      Defensive null-checks before .getRefRecord():
        - if (!current.case || current.case.nil()) - guards against the
          edge case where a task is somehow read without a parent case
          reference. ServiceNow's "case is mandatory" dictionary flag
          (../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_task_case.xml) should prevent
          this at the table-validation layer, but a belt-and-suspenders
          ACL check ensures the script never NPEs against a null reference.
          Returning false here defaults to deny - safer than throwing.
        - if (!parentCase || !parentCase.isValidRecord()) - guards against
          a stale or dangling reference where the parent case sys_id no
          longer resolves to an extant row. .isValidRecord() returns true
          only if the GlideRecord populated by getRefRecord() actually
          fetched a row from the database. Returning false in this branch
          defaults to deny - if we cannot prove the parent case exists,
          we cannot prove the agent has rights on it.
      Both defensive returns are intentional default-deny behavior aligned
      with the principle of least privilege.

    Why gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupId) (not a manual GlideRecord query):
      The platform-supplied gs.getUser() returns the runtime caller's
      GlideUser object, whose isMemberOf(groupSysIdOrName) method is the
      ServiceNow-idiomatic group-membership probe. It internally consults
      the OOB sys_user_grmember join table and the platform's group-
      membership cache; it returns true for both direct AND transitive
      group memberships. Using it instead of a manual `new GlideRecord(
      'sys_user_grmember')` query (a) keeps the ACL script terse and
      auditable, (b) leverages the platform's membership cache for sub-
      millisecond evaluation on hot paths (list rendering, related-list
      population, report execution, dashboard widget data fetch), and
      (c) avoids the failure mode where a custom query forgets to filter
      by `user=` and `group=` and returns false positives. Read-ACL
      evaluation occurs on EVERY row returned by EVERY case_task query,
      so per-row evaluation cost matters disproportionately compared to
      the write path - hence the choice of the cached, idiomatic helper.

    How this ACL composes with parent-case ACLs (defense in depth):
      ServiceNow ACL evaluation is per-table, not transitively inherited.
      Even though x_[scope]_case_task carries a Reference to x_[scope]_case
      via its `case` field, the platform does NOT automatically apply the
      parent case's ACLs to child task records. Each table requires its
      own role-bound ACLs to govern access. This file is therefore
      REQUIRED in addition to ../acl/x_[scope]_case_read_agent_assigned.xml
      - both must apply for a case_agent to be able to (a) open a case
      and (b) see its tasks on the related list. However, by REUSING the
      parent-case predicate (parentCase.assigned_agent /
      parentCase.assigned_group) inside this ACL's script body, we
      guarantee operational consistency: a task is readable by an agent
      if and only if its parent case is readable by that agent. There is
      no scenario where an agent can read a task but not its parent
      case, or vice versa.

    Why <advanced>true</advanced> is REQUIRED (CRITICAL):
      The ServiceNow ACL evaluator only invokes the <script> body when
      <advanced> is true. With <advanced>false</advanced>, the platform
      evaluates only the <condition/> encoded query (which is empty here)
      and the <roles> field, granting read to ANY user holding
      x_[scope]_case_agent regardless of the parent case's assignment.
      This would directly violate AAP Section 0.5.6 and AAP Section 0.7.3
      Gate 3 ("case_agent cannot access unassigned cases") and would
      reduce the agent role on case_task to effectively the same read
      scope as case_viewer (Read=All), collapsing the entire least-
      privilege design. Setting advanced=true ensures the parent-case
      "Assigned only" predicate in the CDATA script body is actually
      evaluated for every case_task read attempt - including direct
      list-view rendering, related-list population on the case form,
      report queries (including the "My overdue tasks" report on the
      Agent Workspace dashboard), GlideRecord queries from Flow Designer
      flows or Script Includes, and any Update Set seed-data round-trips
      at apply time.

    Edge-case behavior (intentional per AAP):
      - Tasks on Draft cases (parent case has no assigned_group, no
        assigned_agent): the parent-case has both fields null, so the
        first branch (parentCase.assigned_agent == currentUserId) returns
        false because null does not equal a real user sys_id, and the
        second branch's groupId is empty so the membership probe is
        skipped. The script-level default-deny clause returns false at
        the bottom. case_agents cannot read tasks on Draft cases - which
        is correct per AAP Section 0.5.5: Draft is a pre-assignment
        status; cases must transition Draft -> Open (with assigned_group
        populated) before agents acquire visibility, and only then can
        tasks under that case be visible to those agents.
      - Tasks on Open cases (parent has assigned_group set but no
        assigned_agent): the first branch returns false (null assignment),
        the second branch checks group membership; any agent who is a
        member of the assigned_group can read the task. This implements
        the "group-level triage visibility" pattern where any group
        member can see incoming task work for their group, supporting
        the operational pickup of unassigned tasks before the parent
        case has been individually assigned to a specific agent.
      - Tasks on cases where the caller is the assigned_agent: the first
        branch short-circuits to true, skipping the group lookup entirely
        and granting read. This is the hot path for an agent's
        operational view of their own task list and avoids the cost of
        a group-membership probe on every row of a list-view render.
      - Tasks on Closed cases (parent.status == Closed): this ACL grants
        read based on assignment, NOT case status. Closed cases remain
        readable to their assigned agents indefinitely so historical
        case-task work remains visible on the agent's "My open cases"
        and "My overdue tasks" reports until those reports' own filters
        (status NOT IN Resolved/Closed; due_date < today) exclude them.
      - admin role: bypasses this ACL entirely via the admin_overrides=true
        attribute below. Platform administrators can always read any
        task in the scope without needing the case_agent role.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section
    0.3.2; no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these
    files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration
        map (`Map&lt;String, List&lt;Object&gt;&gt; rolesToPrivileges`)
        keyed by the property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that
        model, an "agent-equivalent" role would have been associated with
        privilege identifiers such as `acm-task-read` or `acm-task-view`,
        and the per-record "assigned only" check would have been imposed
        at runtime by Spring service classes (e.g., a SecurityFilter
        calling into AcmAssignedObject.getAssignee() on the parent
        CaseFile and comparing against the authenticated principal). The
        ServiceNow target replaces this bifurcated model (declarative
        privilege list + imperative service check) with a single
        declarative scoped record-level ACL whose scripted condition
        body carries the identical predicate. This XML record is the
        direct equivalent of the (case_agent, READ on TASK,
        ASSIGNED-ONLY relative to parent CASE) cell in the conceptual
        ArkCase map.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        plus a private role-name normalization step that uppercased the
        role, replaced whitespace with underscores, replaced periods
        with double-underscores, and prepended the constant `ROLE_`
        prefix from RolePrivilegesConstants). This entire service surface
        is replaced in the ServiceNow target by the platform's built-in
        sys_security_acl evaluator; no scripted privilege resolver is
        needed. The role-name-normalization step in particular is
        replaced by the scoped-application convention of using literal
        scope-prefixed role names (e.g., x_[scope]_case_agent) directly
        in the <roles> field below - no `ROLE_` prefix is prepended, no
        case folding occurs, and the role name is treated as an opaque
        identifier resolved by name against the OOB sys_user_role table.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_[scope] scope (sys_scope = x_[scope], sys_package =
        x_[scope]). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_[scope]_case_task (NOT the OOB
        `task` table or any other global table), and <roles> references
        the scoped role x_[scope]_case_agent. The script body
        dereferences current.case to a row of x_[scope]_case (also a
        scoped table); no global table is accessed.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name
        / source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The CDATA
        script body uses gs.getUserID() (returns the runtime user's
        sys_id, NOT a literal), current.case dereferenced via
        .getRefRecord() (resolves the parent reference at request time
        from the actual stored sys_id, NOT from any literal in this
        XML), and parentCase.assigned_agent / parentCase.assigned_group
        field accesses (resolved by the platform at request time, NOT
        by literal). The <sys_id> below is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key (MD5 of the canonical identifier
        "x_[scope]_case_task.read.case_agent.assigned", a stable key
        for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to any other
        record. Computing the sys_id deterministically guarantees the
        ACL is re-applyable / idempotent across fresh PDIs and round-
        trip Update Set previews per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7.
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_[scope]_case_task`
        with NO dot. Field-level read restrictions on case_task are
        NOT mandated by the AAP for this role; the agent reads all
        permitted fields (case, subject, type, status, assigned_to,
        due_date) on tasks of assigned cases. Field-level write
        restrictions on the CASE table's sensitive columns
        (assigned_group, assigned_agent) are authored separately in
        ../acl/x_[scope]_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
        ../acl/x_[scope]_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml.
      - Operation = read: corresponds exactly to the "Read = Yes
        Assigned only" cell in the AAP matrix, mirrored at the case_task
        level. The other operations (create, write, delete) are authored
        by separate ACL records or enforced by the deliberate absence of
        granting ACLs (deny-by-default for delete).
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required
        so platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or override
        scoped data without needing a case_agent role grant. It does NOT
        widen case_agent privileges - case_agents without admin still
        read only what this ACL permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = true: the script body below IS evaluated at every
        read attempt (see "Why advanced=true is REQUIRED" rationale
        above).
      - condition (empty): no encoded-query condition is set; the entire
        access predicate lives in the scripted body. ServiceNow ACLs
        evaluate condition AND script (both must permit when both are
        present); leaving condition empty defers all logic to the
        script.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped app
          record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_[scope]")
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml (the script dereferences
          current.case to a row of x_[scope]_case; the table must exist
          when the script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case_task.xml (resolves
          <name>x_[scope]_case_task</name>)
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_task_case.xml (the script
          references current.case; the column must exist when the
          script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_assigned_agent.xml (the script
          references parentCase.assigned_agent; the column must exist
          when the script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_assigned_group.xml (the script
          references parentCase.assigned_group; the column must exist
          when the script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_agent.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_[scope]_case_agent</roles> by role name)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml
          (the demo agent's read access to seeded tasks during round-
          trip verification depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - ../seed-data/tasks/x_[scope]_case_task_demo_*.xml (so the
          demo agent immediately sees the seeded synthetic tasks on
          their assigned cases once the Update Set commits, populating
          the case-form Related List, the "My overdue tasks" report,
          and the Agent Workspace dashboard)
        - ../reports/x_[scope]_my_overdue_tasks.xml (the report's row
          set is filtered through this ACL on each evaluation; without
          this ACL the report would either show no rows for case_agent
          users, or - worse, with advanced=false - show ALL overdue
          tasks regardless of assignment, leaking unassigned-case task
          metadata to every agent)
        - ../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_[scope]_agent_workspace.xml
          (consumes the my_overdue_tasks report; same ACL filtering
          applies)

    The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved verbatim per AAP
    convention; the Personal Developer Instance auto-assigns the actual
    concrete scope id at App Engine Studio creation time, and the
    Update-Set apply-time renaming propagates consistently across all
    bracketed placeholders in this artifact.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>true</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Allows users with the x_[scope]_case_agent role to read case_task records ONLY where the parent case has assigned_agent=current user OR assigned_group contains current user.</description>
        <name>x_[scope]_case_task</name>
        <operation>read</operation>
        <roles>x_[scope]_case_agent</roles>
        <script><![CDATA[(function() {
    if (!current.case || current.case.nil()) { return false; }
    var parentCase = current.case.getRefRecord();
    if (!parentCase || !parentCase.isValidRecord()) { return false; }
    var currentUserId = gs.getUserID();
    if (parentCase.assigned_agent == currentUserId) { return true; }
    var groupId = parentCase.assigned_group.toString();
    if (groupId && gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupId)) { return true; }
    return false;
})();]]></script>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>1ea69bf11f64a85ddf0c7e970779fefe</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_[scope]_case_task</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_[scope]_case_task_read_agent_assigned</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>

